HEADWORD: negligee
<hw>neg`li*gee"</hw></mhw>
<pr>(n⟦ecr⟧g`l⟦icr⟧*zh⟦amac⟧"; F. n⟦asl⟧`gl⟦esl⟧`zh⟦asl⟧")</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <altsp>[Also spelled <asp>neglig⟦eacute⟧</asp> and
<asp>neglig⟦eacute⟧e</asp>.]</altsp><ety>[F.
<ets>n⟦eacute⟧glig⟦eacute⟧</ets>, fr. <ets>n⟦eacute⟧gliger</ets> to
neglect, L. <ets>negligere</ets>. See <er>Neglect</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>An easy, unceremonious attire; undress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of loose, flowing dressing gown worn by
women, usually made of sheer fabric.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> negligee, peignoir.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> + <source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Negligence</ent>⟦br⟧
